          "body": "God names the evidence in verses 7-8 with vivid specificity. The priests are offering *blind, lame, and sick* animals. Leviticus 22:17-25 is explicit: no defective animal is acceptable — the entire Mosaic sacrificial system required the unblemished animal as a sign that the worshiper was presenting their best to a holy God. The priests have inverted this. God uses a brilliant rhetorical move in verse 8: 'Why not offer it to your governor? Would he be pleased with you?' The argument is an a fortiori from the lesser to the greater: if civil courtesy demands better than what you're giving God, how much more does the LORD of hosts deserve it. The sarcasm of verse 9 is devastating: 'But now will you not entreat God's favor?' The priests presumably want God to be gracious to the congregation — but they are approaching with the same defiled offering in hand. God's answer is a question that answers itself. You cannot bribe a response from the LORD of hosts with the leftovers you decided He was worth."
