          "body": "Verse 10 is one of the most startling statements in the entire Hebrew prophetic corpus. God says He wishes someone would shut the temple gates and put out the fire on the altar, because He is 'not pleased' with the priests and 'will not accept an offering' from them. This is not hyperbole for rhetorical effect — it is a theological verdict: meaningless religious activity is not neutral. It is worse than nothing, because it gives both worshiper and observer the illusion that something is happening between them and God when nothing is. Isaiah said the same thing centuries earlier (Isaiah 1:11-15): 'I take no delight in your many sacrifices... I cannot endure iniquity and the solemn assembly.' The Lord of hosts would rather have honesty about the emptiness than the noise of a worship service where His name is despised. Tim Keller's observation applies: the primary idol of religious people is not immorality but moralism — using the form of religion to satisfy the conscience without submitting the heart."
