          "title": "The universal name — eschatological worship as the chapter's horizon (1:11)",
          "body": "Verse 11 is the theological climax and the chapter's greatest surprise. After the indictment of Israel's priests, God turns the camera to a future panorama: from the rising of the sun to its setting, His name will be great among the nations, and in every place pure incense and a pure grain offering will be presented. The nations — the Gentiles who had no covenant, no temple, no Levitical priesthood — will offer what Israel's priests have refused to give. This is not merely an embarrassment to Israel; it is the prophetic vision that Psalm 86:9 ('All nations whom You have made shall come and worship before You'), Isaiah 66:20-21, and Zechariah 14:16 share. Conservative commentators debate whether the verse describes something already happening (God-fearers among the Gentiles in Malachi's day) or something entirely future (eschatological worship). The weight of the double 'My name will be great among the nations' — framing the verse like bookends — suggests prophetic future fulfillment. Jesus's Great Commission and John's vision of every tribe and tongue in Revelation 7:9-10 are the New Testament fulfillment. The pure offering Israel withholds will flow from the nations — and the name Israel despises will be feared from the earth's sunrise to its sunset."
